dine or chloropyrimidine\n   - A pyridinol\n\n3. **C-N disconnection (benzene to pyrazole)**: Break the C-N bond. This gives:\n   - A bromo/chloro-benzene\n   - 3-methyl-1H-pyrazole\n\nFor the most direct single-step retrosynthesis, the primary disconnection would be the SNAr reaction forming the aminopyrimidine. The amine nucleophile attacks a chloropyrimidine.\n\nSo the immediate precursors would be:\n- COc1cc(NH2)ccc1-n1cnc(C)c1 (the aniline)\n- Clc2nc(C)cc(Oc3cccnc3)n2 (the chloropyrimidine)\n\nWait, but actually, the question asks for immediate precursors for one retrosynthetic step. Let me think about which disconnection is most strategic.\n\nThe molecule has three key connections:\n1. Aniline NH to pyrimidine C\n2. Pyrimidine C to pyridine O  \n3. Benzene C to pyrazole N\n\nFor a single-step retrosynthesis, I should pick the most obvious/strategic disconnection. The aniline-pyrimidine bond formed via SNAr is very common in medicinal chemistry.\n\nLet me go with the aniline-pyrimidine disconnection:\n\nPrecursor 1: COc1cc(N)ccc1-n1cnc(C)c1 (4-methoxy-3-(3-methyl-1H-pyrazol-1-yl)aniline)\nPrecursor 2: Clc2nc(C)cc(Oc3cccnc3)n2 (2-chloro-4-methyl-6-(pyridin-3-yloxy)pyrimidine)\n\nDisconnection: C-N bond between aniline and pyrimidine (SNAr)\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The target could also be formed by disconnecting the C-O bond between pyrimidine and pyridine, or the C-N bond between benzene and pyrazole.\n\nBut the most common and direct disconnection for this type of molecule (diarylamine on pyrimidine) is the SNAr of an amine on a chloropyrimidine.\n\nLet me finalize:\n\nAnswer: COc1cc(N)ccc1-n1cnc(C)c1; Clc2nc(C)cc(Oc3cccnc3)n2\nDisconnection: C-N bond (aniline-pyrimidine) via SNAr"
